msgid "Using Postfix For Server Process Reporting"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/email/postfix_reporting.md:21
msgid ""
"Complete comfort operating from the command line on a Rocky Linux server"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/email/postfix_reporting.md:21
msgid ""
"Familiarity with an editor of your choice (this document uses the _vi_ "
"editor, but you can substitute in your favorite editor)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/email/postfix_reporting.md:21
msgid "An understanding of DNS (the Domain Name System) and host names"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/email/postfix_reporting.md:21
msgid "The ability to assign variables in a bash script"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/email/postfix_reporting.md:21
msgid "Knowledge of what the _tail_, _more_, _grep_, and _date_ commands do"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/email/postfix_reporting.md:25
msgid ""
"Many Rocky Linux server administrators write scripts to perform specific "
"tasks, like backups or file synchronization, and many of these scripts "
"generate logs that have useful and sometimes very important information. "
"Just having the logs, though, is not enough. If a process fails and logs "
"that failure, but the busy administrator does not review the log, then a "
"catastrophe could be in the making."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/email/postfix_reporting.md:27
msgid ""
"This document shows you how to use the _postfix_ MTA (mail transfer agent) "
"to grab log details from a particular process, and send them to you via "
"email. It also touches on date formats in logs, and helps you identify which "
"format you need to use in the reporting procedure."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/email/postfix_reporting.md:29
msgid ""
"Keep in mind, though, that this is just the tip of the iceberg as far as "
"what can be done with reporting via postfix. Please note, too, that it is "
"always a good security move to limit running processes to only those that "
"you will need all the time."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/email/postfix_reporting.md:31
msgid ""
"This document shows you how to enable postfix only for the reporting you "
"need it to do, and then shut it down again."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/email/postfix_reporting.md:32
#, no-wrap
msgid "Postfix Defined"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/email/postfix_reporting.md:35
msgid ""
"postfix is a server daemon used for sending email. It is more secure and "
"simpler than sendmail, another MTA that was the default go-to MTA for years. "
"It can be used as part of a full-featured mail server."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/email/postfix_reporting.md:36
#, no-wrap
msgid "Installing postfix"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/email/postfix_reporting.md:39
msgid ""
"Aside from postfix, we will need _mailx_ for testing our ability to send "
"emails. To install both, and any dependencies required, enter the following "
"on the Rocky Linux server command line:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/email/postfix_reporting.md:41
msgid "`dnf install postfix mailx`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/email/postfix_reporting.md:43
msgid "!!! warning \"Rocky Linux 9.0 Changes\""
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/email/postfix_reporting.md:45
#, no-wrap
msgid "    This procedure works perfectly fine in Rocky Linux 9.0. The difference here is where the `mailx` command comes from. While you can install it by name in 8.x, `mailx` comes from the appstream package `s-nail` in 9.0. To install the needed packages, you need to use:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/email/postfix_reporting.md:49
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    ```\n"
"    dnf install postfix s-nail\n"
"    ```\n"
msgstr ""

